Findings of 2012

The following variables are selected to see if the difference in income between men and women in 2012 vary depending on them:

  1. race
  2. number.drink.per.day.2012
  3. residence.region.2012
  4. highest.education.2012
  5. family.size.2012
  6. industry.2012

T-Test

Use t.test to test if there is significant difference in income between male and female in 2012.

## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  income.2012 by gender
## t = -17.789, df = 4166.1, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -28793.89 -23077.06
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Female   mean in group Male 
##             30657.24             56592.72

The outcome shows that the average different in income between male and female in 2012 is 2.5935510^{4} dollar, with the p value 0

From the 2 tables, it is found that the difference in income in 2000 vary depending on:
1. Race. The income after square root of hispanic male is 16.1276755 more than that of black male with a p value of 0.0064497, while The income after square root of hispanic female is 14.3837201 more than that of black female with a p value of 0.0147647, so there is 1.7439554 more difference. The income after square root of male of other race is 26.4059212 more than that of black female with a p value of 1.023252210^{-8}. However, there is no significant in difference between other female and black female in income after square root.
2. Number of drink per day. For male, every one more drink per day, the income after square root will decrease by 2.0440732 with a p value of 0.0149007. There is no such significant relationship in female.
3. Region. The income after square root of male in north east is 14.012493 more than that of male in north central with a p value of 0.0134171, while the income after square root of female in north east is 13.794331 more than that of female in north central with a p value of 0.0108489, so there is 0.2181619 more difference.
4. Education year. For male, every one more year of education, the income after square root will increase by 9.6640738 with a p value of 3.308261810^{-32}, while for female, every one more year of education, the income after square root will increase by 12.577473 with a p value of 4.812311410^{-53}. So every one more year of education, the difference narrows by 2.9133992.
5. Family size. For male, every one more person in family, the income after square root will increase by 6.4141271 with a p value of 1.246501610^{-6}, while for female, every one more person in family, the income after square root will decrease by 3.1826383 with a p value of 0.0208385. So every one more person in family, the difference increases by 9.5967654.
6. Industry. Male in some of different industries has significant different income after square root, while there is no significant difference between female in different industries in income after square root.

It is found that whether one has no income in 2012 vary depending on:
1. Race. For hispanic male compared to black male, the odds of having no income decrease by a factor of 1.0797978 with a p value of 0.0028452, but there is no such significant relationship for female. For other male compared to black male, the odds of having no income decrease by a factor of 1.0921255 with a p value of 8.485974410^{-6}, while for other female compared to black female, the odds of having no income decrease by a factor of 1.595625 with a p value of 0.0156555, so the difference narrows by 0.5034995
2. Times of drink per day. For male, every one more drink per day, the odds of having no income decrease by a factor of 0.9911997 with a p value of 0.0147542. For female, every one more drink per day, the odds of having no income decrease by a factor of 0.8903536 with a p value of 0.0432671. So, the difference narrows -0.1008461
3. Education year. For male, every one more year of education, the odds of having no income decrease by a factor of 1.0134649 with a p value of 1.2391710^{-4}. For female, every one more year of education, the odds of having no income decrease by a factor of 1.1614947 with a p value of 5.908528710^{-5}. So, the difference narrows 0.1480298
4. Industry. Male in some of different industries has significant different possible of having no income, while there is no such significant difference between female.

Interaction model

The variabels needed are selected into clean.nlsy.income2012.1. For the income of 2012, the top 2% and zero income data is excluded.

Again, to test whether the income.2000 in clean.nlsy.income2000.1 is normally distributed, qqmorm() and qqline() are used here.

Clearly, income.2012^0.5 (left one) is more normally distributed than income.2012 (right one). Therefore, income.2012^0.5 is used in this interaction regression model.
